<i>Spinus notatus</i>
The <b>Black-headed Siskin</b> (<i>Carduelis notata</i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finch" title="Finch">finch</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fringillidae" title="Fringillidae" class="mw-redirect">Fringillidae</a> family. It is found in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belize" title="Belize">Belize</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Salvador" title="El Salvador">El Salvador</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guatemala" title="Guatemala">Guatemala</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honduras" title="Honduras">Honduras</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicaragua" title="Nicaragua">Nicaragua</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are subtropical or tropical moist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_forest" title="Montane forest" class="mw-redirect">montane forests</a> and heavily degraded former forest.
This species is considered the extant "father" of the South American siskin radiation.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>
This bird is one of the extant parental species of one of the Spinus/Carduelis three evolutive North American radiation which extended to South America after closing of Panama Istmus <sup id="cite_ref-Arnaiz_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Arnaiz-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup>. That of atrata, crassirostris, spinescens, cucullata, yarrelli, magellanica, olivacea, xanthogastra and barbata and a few others.
